Analysis of antibody titers from a bunch of donors

Table of contents

  • Data

  • Antibody titer vs. age

    Linear regression

    Smoothing

  • Prediction

  • Test H2 vaccinated vs. non vaccinated

Data

Data were loaded from several csv files (one per strain) and merged into two dataframes, one for IC50 values and one for the EC50 values.

Data cleaning

IC_50 could not be computed for H5 and H7. For these two strains, rather than the inhibitory concentrations, the inhibition value at the first dilution is reported, expressed in percentage.

EC50 data present two outliers (one in H2 and one in H4 titers): their value for effective concentration was lower than -40 (in log scale) and for this reason were removed.

ec_data$H2_log[ec_data$H2_log < -40] <- NA
ec_data$H4_log[ec_data$H4_log < -40] <- NA

The following plots show the distribution of values, one boxplot per strain. IC50 for H5 and H7 are shown separately because the scale is different (percentage).

IC50

EC50

Merge with donors data

Donors data were taken from the file donors_view.csv in the data/ directory. We excluded donors enrolled in the Novartis study, HIV positive and those for which the number of vaccinations is not defined.

We are left with 271 donors, 141 females and 130 males, for which we can plot the following characteristics. 

## Error: invalid argument to unary operator


##                 
##                   F  M
##   Non vaccinated 55 48
##   Vaccinated     86 82

It is important to point out that the groups are not homogeneous, vaccinated are older than non vaccinated, as seen in the plot below.

## Error: invalid argument to unary operator

We show the boxplots again, limited to donors considered here.

IC50

H3 Brisbane has a few outliers: we remove those below zero.

ic_data$H3_brisbane_log[ic_data$H3_brisbane_log < 0] <- NA

EC50

We observe a few strain with outliers: H1 pandemic 2009, H2 and H4. We remove the lowest observation on each strain.

ec_data$H1_pdm09_log[ec_data$H1_pdm09_log < 0] <- NA
ec_data$H2_log[ec_data$H2_log < -3] <- NA
ec_data$H4_log[ec_data$H4_log < -1.5] <- NA

Analysis of antibody titer: robust linear regression

In the following, we fit a robust linear model to the relation: antibody-titer vs. age. Lots of plots.

Prediction

First of all, it might be instructive to look at a matrix scatterplot of all data. Here below they plots, separated by group just to reduce cluttering.

IC50

EC50

Test on EC50, H2 strain

If we perform a t-test on effective concentration for H2, we do observe a difference between vaccinated and non vaccinated.

t.test(H2_log ~ shot, data = ec_data)

## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  H2_log by shot 
## t = -2.679, df = 239.5, p-value = 0.007888
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0 
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.36034 -0.05498 
## sample estimates:
## mean in group Non vaccinated     mean in group Vaccinated 
##                       0.9937                       1.2014

On the other hand, the difference is all explained by the fact that we are not controlling for the age. In fact, if we perform ANCOVA, age is significant, while age is not.

fit_aov <- aov(H2_log ~ age + factor(shot), data = ec_data)
summary(fit_aov)

##               Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value Pr(>F)    
## age            1   39.9    39.9  146.03 <2e-16 ***
## factor(shot)   1    0.0     0.0    0.07   0.79    
## Residuals    265   72.4     0.3                   
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1 
## 3 observations deleted due to missingness

This is because the average age in the vaccinated is higher (42 vs. 35).

t.test(age ~ shot, data = ec_data)

## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  age by shot 
## t = -4.265, df = 224.3, p-value = 2.949e-05
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0 
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -9.187 -3.380 
## sample estimates:
## mean in group Non vaccinated     mean in group Vaccinated 
##                        35.25                        41.54

Let's make less assumption: we fit with glm (that allows for non-constant variance), and we include an interaction term.

glm_fit <- glm(H2_log ~ age * factor(shot), data = ec_data)
summary(glm_fit)

## 
## Call:
## glm(formula = H2_log ~ age * factor(shot), data = ec_data)
## 
## Deviance Residuals: 
##    Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max  
## -1.867  -0.295  -0.008   0.313   1.691  
## 
## Coefficients:
##                            Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)                 0.19520    0.16680    1.17    0.243    
## age                         0.02253    0.00448    5.03  8.9e-07 ***
## factor(shot)Vaccinated     -0.49137    0.21961   -2.24    0.026 *  
## age:factor(shot)Vaccinated  0.01355    0.00556    2.44    0.016 *  
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1 
## 
## (Dispersion parameter for gaussian family taken to be 0.2684)
## 
##     Null deviance: 112.382  on 267  degrees of freedom
## Residual deviance:  70.851  on 264  degrees of freedom
##   (3 observations deleted due to missingness)
## AIC: 414
## 
## Number of Fisher Scoring iterations: 2

The situation does not exactly get better: we have all terms significant (albeit not by much), but the shot status coefficient alone is negative. As a consequence, the vaccination gives a positive contribution to the EC50 only for donors older than 36. Overall, we don't observe a clear and univoque contribution from the vaccination, while the effect of the age is clear.

In conclusion, I would only consider the age as effective on the titer.

Latest update: 3 April 2013.
